Abstract¶

This report is mainly to analyze the movies in the United States over the past 100 years. Through the study of movie genres, directors, and film elements, we know that people like to watch drama and action movies, some directors do have box office appeal and most of the film's budget and revenue are proportional.

1. Introduction and Background¶

1.1 Background¶

The movie market is booming nowadays, with billion-dollar box-office movies, many of which are American blockbusters. The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) released the 2018 Global Film Entertainment Market Data Report, with north American film market data as the core, showing a profound analysis of the volatile entertainment market. According to the report, global box-office receipts reached 41 billion dollars, including 11.9 billion dollars in North America with a 15 percent increase in film revenue. The number of screen games increased by 7% to nearly 190,000 worldwide. In North America, 1.3 billion moviegoers were seen in 2018, up 5% from 2017. Three-quarters of North Americans (263 million) have seen the film at least once in 2018. Among them, teenagers of 12-17 and 18-24 have the highest average attendance rate, 5.1 per year. with an increase in moviegoers in all except the age of 25-39 and over 60. Besides, Revenue in the U.S. digital home entertainment market rose 24 percent to nearly 17.5 billion dollars, far outpacing a decline of -15 dollars in the physical home entertainment market, which generated 5.8 billion dollars. It shows that movies are closely related to our life. By analyzing the film data, we can know more about people's lifestyles and preferences.

1.2 Introduction¶

This report is mainly to analyze the movies in the United States over the past 100 years, which focus on the following three issues:

  1. The association of different genges in the year, profit, popularity, ratings and the number of people rated.

  2. Explore film numbers, ratings and popularity of the films of director.

  3. Find the variables correlation among runtime, budget, revenue, popularity, ratings and vote count.

2. Methods¶

2.1 Data and Library¶

The datasets is from the the open dataset Kaggle. The web link is https://www.kaggle.com/tmdb/tmdb-movie-metadata. The major database called tmdb_5000_movies, which contains 20 variales about the movie apart from the cast and the crew of the data. In order to enrich the film data, the external dataset tmdb_5000_credits has been added to the major database to provide the directors and actors of movies.

The python libraries, including pandas, numpy, matplotlib.pyplot, datetime, json, LabelEncoder, StandardScaler and PCA, have been imported in this report for analysis.

2.2 Clean Data¶

First, insert tmdb_5000_movies and tmdb_5000_credits and take a view of them.

Then, merged them on movie id to get the dataframe that is used in this project.

Third, this database has a total of 23 variables, but not all variables need to be analyzed, so I delete homepage, original_title, overview, spoken_languages, status, tagline, title_y and movie_id. Looking through the dataframe, there are three missing values. So I complement the three values by looking them up through the internet. Then, I extract year from datetime column, which is useful for the yearly trend.

The most important part of clean data is the way to deal with the json data. To process this kind of data, I loaded json package and wrote functions to process the data. Parsing json data in two steps:

  1. Json data itself is a string type, first converted to a dictionary list, using json.loads().
  2. Then convert the dictionary list to Split string.

2.3 Data Description¶

budget: Budget (USD)

genres: A list of styles, press | Separated, up to 5 styles.

id: The id of the movie from the TMDB.

keywords: A list of keyword movie, press | Separated, up to 5 styles.

original_language: The original_language of the movie.

popularity: Relative page views on Movie Database.

production_companies: Make a list of companies, press | Separated, up to 5 companies.

production_countries: Make a list of contries of the production company, press | Separated, up to 5 companies.

release_date: First release date.

revenue: Revenue (USD).

runtime: Movie duration.

title_x: Movie Name.

vote_average: Average rating.

vote_count: Number of ratings.

actors: List of actors, by | Separated, up to 5 actors.

director: Director's List, press | Separated, up to 5 directors.

year: Year of release.

2.4 Analysis Methodology¶

Given that line charts can show continuous data that changes over time, it is ideal for trends that show data at equal intervals. And a histogram, also known as a mass map, is a major tool for representing changes in data. For the first question, I used line plots and bar charts to show how movies change over time and type.

For the second question, I used bar plots to show the top 20 directors by the count of movies, ratings and budgets.

For the last question, principal component analysis is used to reducing dimensions, 6 key variables to evaluate the films are transformed into two main components to figure out the correlation between the variables.

3.3 Correlation of main variables¶

When we look at movies, we wonder if the relationship between ratings, earnings, and popularity is relevant, in addition to caring about movie categories and cast members. Master component analysis is a multi-statistical method that examines the correlation between multiple variables and studies how to reveal the internal structure between multiple variables through a few main components, exports a few main components from the original variables so that they retain as much information as possible about the original variables and are not related to each other. So we're going to use the main component analysis below to look for the relationship between runtime, popularity, budget, revenue, rating and vote count.

The following image is a PCA diagram for the six variables.

In [378]:
# Set the labels
labels = ['runtime', 'popularity','budget', 'revenue','vote_average','vote_count']

x = mydata[labels] 
y = mydata['title_x'] 
# Scaled the variables
LE = LabelEncoder() 
scaler = StandardScaler() 
scaler.fit(x)
x_scaled=scaler.transform(x)
pca = PCA(n_components=2) 
pca.fit(x_scaled)

In [379]:
# Code from https://stackoverow.com/questions/39216897/ plot-pca-loadings-and-loading-in-biplot-in-sklearn-like-rs-autoplot 
def myplot(score,coeff,labels=None): 
    xs = score[:,0] 
    ys = score[:,1] 
    n = coeff.shape[0] 
    scalex = 1.0/(xs.max() - xs.min()) 
    scaley = 1.0/(ys.max() - ys.min()) 
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
    plt.scatter(xs * scalex,ys * scaley, c = LE.fit_transform(y),s=15) 
    for i in range(n): 
        plt.arrow(0, 0, coeff[i,0], coeff[i,1],color = 'r',alpha = 0.5) 
        if labels is None: 
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, features[i], color = 'g', ha = 'center', va = 'center') 
        else: 
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, labels[i], color = 'g', ha = 'center', va = 'center') 
    plt.xlim(-1,1) 
    plt.ylim(-1,1) 
    plt.xlabel("PC{}".format(1)) 
    plt.ylabel("PC{}".format(2)) 
    plt.title("The PCA plot among important elements of movies")
    plt.grid()
myplot(pca_scores[:,0:2],np.transpose(pca.components_[0:2, :]))

From the plot, we can see that the ratings and runtime have high positive contribution to the second main component with kind of positive contribution to the second main component, while the other four variables have high positive contribution to the first main component with little negative contribution to the second main component. Also, the budgets are kind of proportional to revenue. Besides, the popularity and vote count have almost identical effect on the two main components, which means the more popular the film is, the more people watch it, and more people rate it. To get a more intuitive feel, the side-by-side diagram below shows how much the six variables contribute to the two generated unrelated variables.

Conclusion¶

By analyzing, it comes to four main conclusions.

  1. Animation, adventure, fantasy and action movies are among the top in terms of popularity and earningpower, but require a higher budget for big companies.
  2. Comedy and drama films have low net income, but the single has a high yield and a low budget for small and medium-sized companies.
  3. Different directors will have different box office appeal.
  4. Most films have budgets that are proportional to revenues, and the more popular the film is, the more people rate her.
